id: pm-lnrk
title: "Wave 2 terminal-history graph backfill: reconstruct closed and canceled lineage in changelog-safe, epoch-ordered batches"
description: "Enrich terminal item relationships only after active graph policy is proven, preserving historical meaning and coordinating every mutation with changelog and resolution-evidence governance."
type: Task
status: open
priority: 3
tags[8]: backfill,changelog-safe,graph,history,relationships,task,terminal-items,"wave:2"
created_at: "2026-07-13T22:00:29.132Z"
updated_at: "2026-07-13T22:00:29.132Z"
author: codex-root
estimated_minutes: 1800
acceptance_criteria: "Start only after Wave 1 policy and tooling are accepted and pm-e9zh terminal evidence workflow is unblocked or explicitly coordinated; Partition terminal work by historical epoch, canonical parent lineage, release or incident boundary, and bounded batch size with non-overlapping claims; Infer candidate edges only from durable evidence such as original descriptions, comments, history events, linked commits or PRs, files, docs, tests, releases, and explicit identifiers; Human review is required for ambiguous retyping, inferred prerequisites, conflicting evidence, and high-impact graph hubs; unresolved cases retain uncertainty rather than fabricated links; Corrections append superseding events and preserve prior versions; each item remains restorable and explainable at every snapshot; Every batch includes package-owned changelog generation and review after the final tracker mutation plus duplicate, lifecycle, graph, health, history-chain, and release-boundary validation; Completion classifies every terminal item and demonstrates bounded resumability, stable indexes, and compact audit summaries at million-item scale"
goal: project management = context management
objective: "Recover decades-scale historical lineage and evidence without rewriting proof, dragging unrelated changelog buckets, or inventing retrospective certainty"
value: "Agents and graph algorithms can learn from completed, canceled, superseded, and failed work as first-class institutional context"
impact: "Enables point-in-time restoration, analogical retrieval, outcome learning, provenance, release archaeology, and trustworthy long-horizon planning"
outcome: "Epoch-ordered terminal graph batches with immutable supersession events, changelog review, uncertainty labels, and complete validation evidence"
why_now: "Terminal items are most of the tracker and carry rich history, but they also present the highest semantic, audit, and changelog risk"
parent: pm-a8zm
risk: high
confidence: low
